<h1><span id="Ruy_Lopez_Main_Line">Ruy Lopez Main Line</span></h1>
<h2><span id="8._d4.3F.21"></span><span id="8._d4?!">8. d4?!</span></h2>
<p>White counts the number of pieces attacking d4, and the number of pieces defending it, and reckons that 8. d4 is a safe move.
</p>
<h2><span id="8._d4.3F_Nxd4.21_9._Nxd4_exd4_10._Qxd4"></span><span id="8._d4?_Nxd4!_9._Nxd4_exd4_10._Qxd4">8. d4? Nxd4! 9.  Nxd4 exd4 10. Qxd4</span></h2>
<p>Alas, Black plays 10...c5! and wherever her beautifully centralised queen moves, Black follows up with 11...c4 and the b3-bishop is trapped. (third diagram)
</p><p>The moral of the story: White must prepare d4 with 8. c3.
</p>
